begin_memory_text: I asked her if she was in school. She told me she was studying Human Resources because she loves people and wants the work environment to be a great place. A dream led her to her career choice. She told me she liked my shirt because of its color. I  told her she can buy it from Walmart.
middle_memory_text: She asked my favorite holiday. I told her Christmas because of  my daughter. She is super excited about receiving her suggested gift ‘princess car.’ I told her how dedicated she was about this gift and how she put in her order to Santa through an app, mail a letter to Santa, called her grandparents about her present.
end_memory_text: We talked about the snow. She asked if I lived in the snow and I said I use to in MN. She asked how it was like. I told her it was cold but nice. How living in MN you get to experience all the seasons and really get to enjoy the beauty of nature.
rest_of_day_open: I see my week being very busy. I have a paper I am writing that I need to have completed. Furthermore, I have the kids in school which is going to be very hard as we are doing virtual school. Also, getting the house together for the holidays is going to be challenging with the kids home. However, I am looking forward to preparing for the holidays.
critical_positive: I think I worked well for the conversation. I don’t want to be rude but we had nothing in common so, I kept trying to find things to talk about. She was very specific and didn’t want to go into details. Thus it made the conversation very hard and mechanical.
critical_negative: I think the age difference was a problem. I guess we couldn’t find something that we could engage in that would be substantial. Nevertheless, she was close minded. Meaning she didn’t want to give to much of herself to a stanger. I guess finding dialogue or letting someone who you don’t know into your personal life even generally was something she didn’t necessarly want.

begin_memory_text: We talked about how we were doing which was 'pretty good', that she had just gotten up from bed and was active because she wasn't feeling well all day, that my weekend was just studying, we also talked about what tea she had been drinking and we also talked about Tik Tok and the social medias she had gotten into (Facebook, then Instagram, then Tik Tok) She got into Tik Tok because one of her students told her about the app
middle_memory_text: We talked about how she lived in Minneapolis, what the weather was like, that she lived in FL, she talked about how she loved living there and experiencing all the seasons, and that it doesn't snow very much in FL. She mentioned that at the time, she was in college and her friends had cars, but she did not. She reminisced about long boots and short miniskirts that she wore back then and that there were tunnels between the dorms at the college she went to. She asked about if I go to online school or if I take my classes in person, what my major was and what lead me to choose it.
end_memory_text:
Towards the end of the conversation, we talked about her name and what it meant. I asked her if she was comfortable with sharing her name and then she said it didn't have a name, but her granddad wrote her first name on a piece of toilet paper and told her mom "this is what you will name her". We also talked about how she had a headache beforehand but she was feeling better, and that after the conversation she would likely go get some work done. 2 minutes before the call ended, I requested that she and I chat for another minute because I had joined the call at 8:01 and it was only 8:25 at the time. Before the call ended, we said it was nice to meet each other and I encouraged her to take her to take all the time she needed, and I mentioned that I was sure that she gave her own name meaning and she said that her life the past 10 years is largely a blessing so she would say that her name means blessing.

In the 'memory of beginning of the conversation" portion, I forgot to mention how she talked about her daughter and her daughter's dedication to letting everyone know what she wanted for Christmas (downloaded apps to tell Santas, told her mom, dad and grandmother on the mom's side and the dad's side), and that she loved and impressed by her daughter's gratitude and humbleness for even for the little things. She also mentioned that Christmas was her favorite holiday (I realize that this is the wrong section to type this in but she was very thorough and passionate about it, so although this is typed at a later section that I should have typed it in, this is an ode to that memory. Thank you, and I apologize for any inconvenience this may cause)

critical_positive: There was always something to talk about, my conversation partner always had something to say, and there wasn't any question that neither of us didn't respond to. We were open with each other and it was an overall positive interaction. I like that we added to each other's ideas, and moods.
critical_negative: What didn't work very well was I noticed that my answers were much shorter than my conversation partner's answers, and that my conversation partner was talking the majority of the time and I noticed it was sometimes felt hard to bring up a new topic and ask questions. At times, the conversation felt really natural, but at times, it did not and thus I didn't feel very open.
